Eric Pastore  
August 8, 2025

This report is for the “Sponsorship ROI and Brand Lift Reports” section for the Sports Advertising Analytics Project.  The sports game/event that was chosen was the Super Bowl LVIII in 2024\.  Although there was limited public data available, Super Bowl LVIII still showed some interesting results, including the total number of impressions for each sponsor, the segments with the highest sponsor visibility, how brand awareness and favorability improved after campaigns, activations that led to measurable user actions, and the ROI of sponsoring the halftime show along with digital overlays during the game.

1. How many impressions did the sponsor’s logo/brand receive during the game?

During the 58th Annual Super Bowl, several sponsors were advertised a total of 63 times all together during the game, including Apple Music, Budd Light, Nike, State Farm, etc.  Across all of the sponsors, Nike had received the most impressions, totaling 60% of all ads (38) impressions during the Super Bowl.

![][image1]

2. Which segments of the broadcast or event had the highest sponsor visibility?

While each segment in the Super Bowl had , the ones with the highest sponsor visibility were Nike, Apple Music, and State Farm.  Since Nike had the most impressions during the Super Bowl, it makes sense that it generated the most profit and gained the most screen time, earning over $170 million dollars in revenue and 2195 seconds (36 and a half minutes) of total screen time.  

While Nike was the most profitable sponsor with the most total screen time, the Apple Music halftime show was the most popular segment, garnering 129.3 million views on YouTube, making it the most-watched Super Bowl halftime show to date. 

Lastly, State Farm launched a campaign that encouraged viewers to predict how many times they \[State Farm\] would be mentioned during the Super Bowl.  This campaign had received 315 million total views on social media, making it the most popular Super Bowl Campaign to date.

![][image2]

3. Did brand awareness or favorability improve after the campaign? 

Yes, brand awareness and favorability did improve after the campaigns during the 58th annual Super Bowl LVIII.  Outside of the State Farm Campaign, other campaigns included “Born to Play,” “Tackle Bullying,” and “Mental Game.”.  According to The Harris Poll, these three national ad campaigns increased brand quality, Purchase Consideration, Brand Familiarity, Perceived momentum, and the Percentage describing the brand as “stylish” grew by 11, 7.2, 7, 6.5, and 5 percent respectively.

![][image3]

 	From February 5-18, YouGov tracked and measured Ad Awareness, Buzz, and Purchase Consideration changes among the 63 total Super Bowl LVIII advertisers using surveys by comparing the two weeks (February 5-11 and February 12-18).  During these two weeks, Veylinx had conducted a behavioral study on the demand of advertised products before and after the Super Bowl.  They found an overall 16.4% increase in demand for advertised products, with 24% more demand across male viewers, a 9% increase across female viewers, and a 11% increase in demand among Gen Z viewers.  The last group (Gen Z viewers) had demanded more because of the “Taylor Swift Effect”, which is when products and advertisements reach younger audiences.

![][image4]

Lastly, System1 scored the results of advertisement feedback using two metrics, Spike Rating and Star rating, which represent the short-term sales of the product and the long-term effectiveness of the brand, respectively.  Although System1 did not record the short-term results of these ads, they did find the 3 most successful long-term sponsors along with their star ratings: Michelin’s ULTRA “Superior Beach” at 4.8 stars, Reese’s “Yes\!” at 4.7 stars, and Hellmann’s “Mayo Cat” at 4.5 stars.  This is because these 3 ads included popular characters along with an emotional story.

![][image5]

Overall, brand awareness and favorability improved significantly for many Super Bowl LVIII advertisers.  The Harris Poll explained that the NFL itself had experienced increases in perception, consideration, familiarity, and “momentum.”,  consumers had increased demand for products—especially men, Gen Z, and viewers influenced by targeted campaigns, and ads that prioritized emotional storytelling or memorable characters (rather than just celebrity presence) generally scored better for long-term brand support.

4. Which activations led to measurable user actions (clicks, scans, mentions, purchases)?

Although several activation methods were used during Super Bowl LVIII, 6 of them led to measurable user actions:

* QR Codes  
* Clicks  
* Social Mentions  
* Engagement Ads  
* Online Interaction  
* EMV and Pre-Game activations

During Super Bowl LVIII, overall QR code scans increased by approximately 18%.  This is primarily because Miller Lite and DoorDash incorporated QR codes into their ads.  Miller Lite embedded their codes into jerseys, whereas DoorDash applied QR codes for sweepstakes.  These two uses of QR codes helped drive scan-based engagement across viewers.  Just like Miller Lite and DoorDash, Coinbase also used QR codes for their ads.

![][image6]

Coinbase’s “Long Live Crypto” advertisement, which featured a QR code, resulted in a massive increase of 1480% in hourly website visits, a 347% increase in daily account signups, and a substantial social media volume of approximately 562 thousand users.  In addition to Coinbase, other big companies like Budweiser, Amazon, and GM also gained popularity in social media.

![][image7]

Budweiser, with their “Snow Day” ad, was mentioned on social media 746,000 times, which increased search interest for the product by \+35% and increased purchase intent by \+26%.  Amazon’s advertisement featuring Alexa, titled “I told you so”, was mentioned on social media a total of 328,000 times, which in turn increased search interest on Alexa by 19% and increased consumers’ purchase intent by 14%.  Lastly, GM’s “The New Power Couple”, which was hosted on Chevy and Netflix, was mentioned on social media 281,000 times, resulting in an 24% increase in interest and a 16% increase in favorability.

T-Mobile, with their “A New Era in Connectivity” ad increased its online engagement by 12.6 times as opposed to the average Super Bowl ad, “Drive Your Own Story” by Ram, which only increased its online engagement by a factor of 8.5.  These ads, along with others, allowed Super Bowl LVIII to have a total of over 2.8 billion online engagements across Social media.  Nike’s ad, titled “So Win”, received 13 thousand online mentions alone, which was the most amount of online mentions of any sponsorship brand that year.  While all of these sponsors were mentioned and viewed during Super Bowl LVIII, some brands, such as E.L.F. and CeraVe, used activation methods before the Super Bowl even began, going back as far as January 2024\.

![][image8]

![][image9]

![][image10]

Between February 1-12, E.L.F grossed a total of 11.7 Million dollars in Eared Media Value (or EMV for short) during its pre-game campaign.  Likewise, CeraVe’s Michael Cera Spot obtained a total EMV of $1,200,000 using \#MichaelCeraVe posts, along with an additional $883,000 from \#MichaelCeraTags in January.

![][image11]

Overall, the activation methods that led to measurable user actions were QR code scans, Clicking on websites, Mentions on social media, High-Engagement ads, Online Interactions, and even Earned Media Values before Super Bowl LVIII even began.

5. What is the ROI of sponsoring halftime shows vs. digital overlays?

	The Super Bowl LVIII halftime show was sponsored by Apple Music.  This halftime show resulted in one of the most-watched live performances in history, reaching nearly 130 million viewers on social media.  However, the artists who performed in the halftime show received no payment, meaning that there is no realistic way to measure the halftime show’s ROI.  Nonetheless, these artists noticed large increases in streams and long-term sales.  For example, people who viewed the Super Bowl LVIII halftime show caused Shakira and J. Lo’s music consumption to increase between 267% and 893%.  This is because Apple Music relies heavily on emotional brand association, extended engagement through playlists, exclusive content, and cultural relevance.  Digital Overlays on the other hand, could be analyzed to produce quantifiable ROI results.![][image12]

![][image13]

	According to Relo Metrics, Sponsor Media Value per exposure during Super Bowl LVIII was estimated to be around $457,400 dollars, an increase of 7% as opposed to last year.  With a total of nearly 500,000 brand exposures, this led to a total Sponsor Media value of approximately $228 billion with a total screen time (for all exposures) of 15.4 million seconds (\~178 days).  Out of all the brands, Nike had the most screen time of 2195 seconds (36 and a half minutes), translating to a Vision Value of $69,500,000.  Other notable Digital Overlay brands included State Farm with a vision value of $16,000,000, Allegiant Stadium Signage at $7,300,000, Aerial Shots of Las Vegas hotels at $4,100,000, Verizon’s Sphere takeover at $2,500,000, and the Chiefs’ Social media exposure during the weekend at $10,600,000.

![][image14]

Ultimately, Digital overlays and branding during the game delivered strong, measurable ROI through direct media valuation—ranging from $2,000,000 to over $70,000,000 depending on how large the overlays were, as well as how many people were able to see them.  The halftime show sponsorship, on the other hand, did not have a quantifiable ROI, but encouraged deeper brand connections, cultural relevance, and long-term engagement, which can lead to returns and profit in the long run.
